It just so happened that I was also watching the island with Bear Grylls, Series 2, episode 7, and in his intro, he also does an aerial view of the island. Itâ€™s the same island. Now what this means is that we can research where series two of the island with Bear Grylls was filmed. This tells us that it was filmed at the Pearl Island chain off of the coast of Panama, the Pacific Ocean side. The specific island in this video is Isla Pedro Gonzalez and there is a village on the island of the same name. Home to a marina, hotel and resort and all kinds of really awesome and fun amenities including a resort called the Pearl Island Ritz reserve which offers luxury amenities to those who can afford it. No, you cannot eat a Halloween moon crab. The Halloween moon crab (Gecarcoidea natalis) is a species of land crab that lives in certain areas of the Pacific coast. They are only active at night and are usually seen gathering in large groups near sources of moisture such as wet leaves, streams and rocks.  These crabs are held in high regard by cultural groups in their native regions, particularly in Hawaii and parts of Polynesia, who view them as a sacred and revered symbol. Thatâ€™s why consuming it is often forbidden, as its life cycle is purely for protecting the environment and for cultural purposes.

A few things... Not a survivalist in any way but... Raised on a sailboat as a kid rationing water, collecting rain, fish coconuts... for 6 years... hmm I finally like fish again when I season it my way but there is no way I'm payin the high prices... GRRRR  So as others have stated "EAT THE CRABS"!!! Make crab soup etc. for only 72hrs it may not be worth it but I always notice that seldom do these adventurists EXPLORE, ASSESS, PLAN. I think it is worthwhile to make fish capturing a primary. Either netting, or funneling into a small area etc. so you make it once and it fishes for you. Screw a hook when you can corral them into a pen. That is where the crabs come in.. bait, trap bait, trap...   Second, work at night and sleep during the day, dig down into the earth to keep cool. I really liked her idea of the slippery bottles to keep craps out but poorly executed!!! Again sleep during the day and work by fire light and smoke during the night. Gather in the dawn or dusk light and set up for working area and capture the crabs with fish bate... what do they want? Give it to them and that will keep them away too. I'm thinking of using the plastic slippery as a cliff kinda thing or a basket with a one way entry.    Yes good point to keeping cool, bath often and let the salt dry on the skin for better cooling and keeps the bugs away. Not sure where but find out a source of vitamin C ... taking lots of it keeps bugs away somewhat too.   What the hell do sand flees like what do they hate? Give em what they like over there and put what they hate over here. Sleep being essential it might be wise to take bug, fire, crab shifts so sleepers can sleep well. With four people it is easy rotation of 3 or 4 hrs. I like 3 hrs because everyone can do 3 hrs, and everyone gets 9hrs of solid sleep or 6hrs and 3hrs everyone working together.    As to the best coconut harvesting tool.. you were so close.. I was the climber in the family so no one had to worry I was awesome climber and as a small child I learned the best technique is to twist or spin the coconut till it breaks loose, So I'd make a pouch type of sticky or sharp spike grabber that would grab the coconut and then you spin it and it falls into your pouch or the ground. Knowing that coconuts are not round I'd take advantage of that fact. So lift spin and drop. Tons of coconuts.   Third Learn how to use a machete!!! When you cut ALWAYS cut diagonally with the grain... it will walk through it ... I can and do cut through 4inch branches in one slice... hit either away or towards the tree. Slice as close to sturdy tree as possible then put on solid ground spot and slice slice slice. I had two chain saws crap on me on a job so i used two machetes to take down three Pine trees, cut up into fire length and kindling. They were 12 inches, 9 inches and one was 15inches at the base. All cut up, stacked and done in about 5 hours.  Stay cool by keeping a bucket of water and soak shirt and hang around neck.   So hopefully this is helpful to anyone doing this or finding themselves in survival situation. Oh the right edge on the machete is essential and the longer the better!! Use the wrist at the end of the swing like a trebuchet action, less energy way more power and then add technique stated above and life is good, work is easy and survival becomes thriving.  For me  1. Water and water collection!!  2. traps for whatever may be edible or pesky 3. shelter - again personally I go into the ground and cover, both in really cold and really hot. I stayed a few nights in a home built in the sand with bamboo holding the sand at different levels. Truly amazing, simple and protected, sturdy and the roof could catch the breeze and funnel it. 4. fire... I put it last because once you have one you have to feed it all the time... screw that, .. either learn to get really good at starting a fire (ummmm glass bottles to magnify??) or again dig a ditch to hold the heat and keep a small fire or just ambers to start one with or rocks etc anything to keep the heat in and can be used to keep warm if someone gets chills due to rain, loss of energy etc.    If I were to bring one thing it would have to be netting as in keep all bugs out netting!!!! Other than a machete of course!!   Great stuff and so glad to see others live real life every now and then... it is "altering" experience and I think everyone should be required to do such before graduating from HS, instead of "Spring break" of debauchery, better to learn life skills.   BTW, When God Blessed you with rain, give thanks were thanks is justified. Remember God made the entire universe and then one tiny stable sun with planets and one special one with a moon that has a rotation, on a tilted axis and magnetic field and WATER... I think a little appreciation is warranted. It makes a difference too.  Science has shown that if one, just one little thing, distance from the sun, size of the sun, tilt of the axis, no magnetic field, moon smaller, larger, closer, further away, rotation speed, every little thing altered one teeny tiny bit and we would not exist... hmmm pretty awesome eh?? Thank you Creator!!! You are wonderful and amazing!! Blessings

I do enjoy survival situations  - though if I may....72 hours with no food or (fresh) water on an island with a shady spot under some trees is not really surviving anything, simply because...well...you can live without any food or water at all for 72 hours and be just fine. I know because I've done it - I've gone nearly 2 weeks without food and 4 days without water before (I was REALLY hungry after the first few days, then I hit a period where my stomach got USED to being empty and I wasn't bothered by it so much and a bit of water here and there was enough - it was only after week 1 that I started to run into dizzy spells standing up and feeling pretty weak by day 10 and 11). You'd be pretty dehydrated, for sure, and a bit hungry yes but there's very little risk of actually dying within that time period if you went INTO the situation reasonably well fed and hydrated (which I'm sure you would have). This is more like a camping trip where you forgot to take food and water. It'd suck but it'd be fine as long as you got water in  you before day 5. Technically you can live for a MONTH without any food though by week 3 you'd be so weak you'd be barely able to get up and walk around, which is where the danger comes in.   Anyway my point is, 10 days to 2 weeks would be a survival situation since you CAN die from lack of water in that time (not food though) and anything over 3 weeks becomes a serious survival situation without food. Thoughts for future videos ;)

For 10 days, I couldnâ€™t walk the 12 feet, from my bed, to the bathroom, until about four days before I was discharged. I wasnâ€™t hungry, during my COVID stint, because my body was in complete survival mode, and I thought I was going to vomit every little thing I ate back up. I was so exhausted that I was more scared to lose energy from vomiting than I was to starve potentially to death. The nurse and my family finally convinced me if I didnâ€™t eat, I would be forced to, and I wouldnâ€™t like the way it would happen. Â @Joshstix95Â : See, one of the first things I would do upon landing there is to scout out and find the trash. Sad it is there, it is everywhere, but it does have great survival uses. First thing is to clean and use plastic to set up a solar fresh water distillation system. Next, sort all plastic I could turn into shingles. Some for cordage. Storage. The shingles along with the hybiscus bark cordage and a rain proof roof and side walls would have been a priority. Use palm fronds to weave walls, bed mats, and a door. This would minimize and even eleminate the invasion of the crabs and the flies. And no shelter under any trees that can drop heavy objects on me and or my shelter. Fun video.  I personally have quite a bit of experience with fasting.  I'm currently on an OMAD diet (one meal a day).  And haver personally done fasts over 100 hours (4 days).   Water is critical.  Food is not.  When in a fasted state I often have more energy.  There is a huge difference between a fasted state and a starvation state.   Having limited food throughout the day works your digestive system (breaks a fast) and puts you into a state of starvation and that might be worse than eating nothing at all.   It would be better to save your food for one larger meal than eating not enough through the day.   When in a fasted state your digestive system goes dormant and your body prioritizes energy for acquiring food and critical thinking.   I'm most energetic and clear when in a fasted state.   It often takes me 8 to 12 hours of no calories to enter a fasted state.   Of note dehydration is bad all around and water is very important for your body to convert fat to glucose to make energy.
